    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-22T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-22T06:00:00-05:00" n="807"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d807">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.6363/299: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-22T20:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 22, 1936—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 22—12:13 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>265. Embassy’s 264, December 19, 6 p.m., paragraph 6.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The local representatives of the oil interests have today asked that at
                        least some preliminary diplomatic approach to the Japanese <pb facs="0899"
                            n="804" xml:id="pg_804"/> Government be made either in Washington and
                        London or in Tokyo before the holidays—(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) because
                        not having fulfilled the storage promises the foreign oil companies are in
                        the position of lawbreakers and are liable as penalization to have their
                        1937 sales quotas reduced unless they are supported by diplomatic measures
                            and—(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) because the anticipated approval by the
                        Tariff Investigation Commission of the proposed revision of the petroleum
                        tariff should be forestalled. Any discriminatory tariff revision as the
                        Department is aware would be contrary to the oral assurances given the oil
                        companies. It is expected that the 1937 quota will be allotted and the
                        tariff revision examined within the next few days.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I shall, however, take no action here without the Department’s
                        authorization and unless the British Ambassador takes an approximately
                        simultaneous and similar step. Clive informs me that he is cabling similarly
                        and urgently to London tonight.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
